# IMU-only Error-State Kalman Filter Formulation

## 1. Purpose

This file documents the custom Python IMU-only ESKF baseline used for orientation estimation from accelerometer and gyroscope data.

The goal is not to estimate full position or velocity. The current filter estimates sensor orientation and gyroscope bias only.

The filter uses:
- gyroscope measurements for quaternion propagation
- accelerometer measurements as a gravity-direction correction for roll and pitch
- no magnetometer, so absolute yaw/heading is not observable

---

## 2. Coordinate and Quaternion Convention

Quaternion convention: q = [qw, qx, qy, qz]

The implementation uses Hamilton quaternion multiplication.

Euler angles are used only for plotting and interpretation. The filter state itself is propagated using quaternions.

Gyroscope measurements are converted to: rad/s

Accelerometer measurements are kept in: g

for the gravity-direction update, because the accelerometer measurement is normalised before correction.

---

## 3. Nominal State

The nominal state is: x = { q, b_g }

where:
q   = orientation quaternion
b_g = gyroscope bias, 3x1

The nominal state dimension is not treated as 7 additive states because the quaternion lies on SO(3). Instead, the covariance is maintained over a 6-dimensional error state.

---

## 4. Error State

The error state is: δx = [ δθ, δb_g ]ᵀ

where:
δθ   = small attitude error, 3x1
δb_g = gyroscope bias error, 3x1

The covariance matrix is:
P = cov(δx)

so:
P is 6 x 6

with structure:
P[0:3, 0:3] = attitude error covariance
P[3:6, 3:6] = gyro bias covariance

---

## 5. Prediction Model

The bias-corrected angular rate is: ω = ω_m - b_g
where:
ω_m = measured gyroscope angular rate
b_g = estimated gyroscope bias

The nominal quaternion is propagated using: q_{k+1} = q_k ⊗ Exp(ω Δt)

The gyroscope bias is modelled as slowly varying: b_{g,k+1} = b_{g,k} 

with small process noise.

---

## 6. Error-State Prediction

The current implementation uses a first-order discrete-time approximation of the continuous error dynamics.

The discrete error transition matrix is:
F_d =
[ I - [ω]x Δt    -I Δt ]
[ 0               I    ]

where:  [ω]x is the skew-symmetric matrix of the angular rate.

The covariance is propagated as: P_{k+1} = F_d P_k F_dᵀ + Q_d

The current process noise approximation is:
Q_θ ≈ σ_g² Δt I
Q_bg ≈ σ_bg² Δt I

This is a first-order discrete approximation, not an exact matrix-exponential discretisation.

---

## 7. Accelerometer Measurement Model

The accelerometer is used as a gravity-direction measurement.

The measured acceleration is normalised: z = a_m / ||a_m||

The predicted gravity direction in the sensor/body frame is: h(q) = predicted_gravity_body(q)

The residual is: r = z - h(q)

This correction mainly observes roll and pitch. Without a magnetometer, yaw is not directly observable.

Accelerometer update is skipped if the accelerometer norm is too far from 1g, because this indicates significant linear acceleration.

Current gate: 0.8g < ||a_m|| < 1.2g

---

## 8. Measurement Jacobian

The current implementation uses a numerical finite-difference Jacobian:

H[:, j] = (h(q ⊕ ε_j) - h(q)) / ε

This is used initially to avoid sign and frame-convention errors.

A future improvement is to replace this with an analytic Jacobian after the quaternion and frame conventions have been fully validated.

---

## 9. Kalman Update

The standard Kalman correction is:

S = H P Hᵀ + R
K = P Hᵀ S⁻¹
δx = K r

where: δx = [δθ, δb_g]ᵀ

The covariance is updated using the Joseph form: P = (I - K H) P (I - K H)ᵀ + K R Kᵀ

This helps preserve symmetry and positive semi-definiteness numerically.

---

## 10. Error Injection

After the Kalman update, the estimated error state is injected into the nominal state.

Attitude injection: q ← q ⊗ Exp(δθ)

Gyroscope bias injection: b_g ← b_g + δb_g

The current implementation uses right-side attitude injection.

---

## 11. Error Reset

After injection, the error state is reset to zero.

The current prototype uses the small-angle approximation: G ≈ I

so the reset covariance transform is approximated as: P ← P

A more formal reset Jacobian can be added later if needed.

---

## 12. Current Limitations

The current filter is an IMU-only orientation ESKF baseline.

Limitations:

* no magnetometer, so absolute yaw is not observable
* no position or velocity state
* accelerometer correction assumes acceleration is mostly gravity
* covariance discretisation uses a first-order approximation
* accelerometer Jacobian is numerical, not analytic
* reset Jacobian is currently approximated as identity
* Euler angles are only for plotting; final relative orientation should use quaternion-relative rotation

---

## 13. Current Validation Status

Static 20s dataset:

* timestamp and sampling rate verified
* accelerometer norm stable near 1g
* gyro static bias observed and estimated from initial static period
* relative roll/pitch stable
* yaw drift observed as expected
* yaw covariance grows as expected because yaw is unobservable in IMU-only setup

